ce:section.ce:para:
Molecular imaging with theranostic nanoplatforms can serve as powerful tools for siRNA-based therapeutic product development and optimization of disease management (Fig. 1
                  ), through the in vivo monitoring of the siRNA delivery process and therapeutic efficacy (Liu, Swierczewska, Lee, & Chen, 2010; Moore & Medarova, 2009). Generally, a variety of theranostic nanosystems have been used for multiple molecular imaging modalities guided in vivo siRNA delivery and silencing, including positron emission tomography (PET) and single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT) imaging (radioisotope integrated organic/inorganic nanoparticles); optical fluorescence imaging (semiconductor/carbon/silica/Ag2S quantum dots, single-walled carbon nanotubes, colloidal gold nanoparticles) (Wang et al., 2015); magnetic resonance imaging (MRI contrast agents, mainly iron oxide-based magnetic nanoparticles (IOMNPs)); ultrasound (US, microbubbles) and computed tomography (CT contrast agents, e.g., gold nanoparticles) (James & Gambhir, 2012; Liu et al., 2010). In fact, most imaging modalities have limited use due to their significant shortcomings: PET and SPECT lack anatomic information that needs to be compensated by the combination of CT or MRI (Pichler, Judenhofer, & Pfannenberg, 2008). Besides, using radionuclide/X-ray imaging techniques poses safety risks when exposed to ionizing radiation, which limits the number of scans for the same patient in a period of time (Pichler et al., 2008). Optical fluorescence imaging is limited by its superficial penetration (<1cm) because of light scattering and autofluorescence in tissues, which needs to be improved by using near-infrared (NIR) fluorescence imaging (Lee, Park, Hong, Choi, & Choi, 2012; Wang et al., 2015). US is also limited by its depth of penetration. By contrast, MRI shows a number of superiorities compared with other imaging modalities including: (1) the whole body imaging without depth limitation; (2) high spatial resolution: ~1mm; (3) no ionizing radiation exposure; (4) excellent soft tissue contrast; and (5) high clinical utility (James & Gambhir, 2012). However, the poor signal sensitivity of MRI can result in prolonged acquisition times (James & Gambhir, 2012). To overcome this major limitation and simultaneously achieve concurrent siRNA-based therapy for theranostic purposes, multifunctional magnetic nanoparticles have been developed for high sensitivity targeted MRI-guided siRNA delivery (Xing, Liu, Zhu, Hou, & Chen, 2014). In particular, IOMNPs have generated a sustained interest because of their versatility (not only their unique magnetic properties, but also a well-developed surface functionalization for active targeting, loading, and controlled release of siRNA) and a reasonable safety profile (biodegradability and low toxicity) (Jain, Reddy, Morales, Leslie-Pelecky, & Labhasetwar, 2008; Medarova, Pham, Farrar, Petkova, & Moore, 2007; Xie, Liu, Eden, Ai, & Chen, 2011; Yoo, Lee, Shin, & Cheon, 2011). Presently, a variety of IOMNP formulations have been clinically approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and the European Medicines Agency (EMA) for MR imaging and therapeutic applications (Table 1
                  ; Sun, Lee, & Zhang, 2008; Wang, 2011; Singh & Sahoo, 2014).

In addition to co-precipitation methods, the thermal decomposition of organometallic precursors in high-boiling organic solvents has been specifically developed for the synthesis of monodispersed IOMNPs and Fe-M alloy nanoparticles that offer enhanced magnetism and advanced homogeneous control over the crystallinity and morphology. Various organometallic precursors, including metal acetylacetonates: [M(acac)
                        n
                     ], cupferronate: [M(C6H5N2O2)
                        n
                     ], pentacarbonyl: [M

                        x
                     (CO)
                        n
                     ], and acetate: [M(C2H3O2)
                        n
                     ], (where the M = Mn, Zn, Fe, Co, Ni; n depends on the oxidation number of M) are often used for thermal decomposition in non-aqueous solvents containing stabilizing surfactants (Jeong, Teng, Wang, Yang, & Xia, 2007). Thereby, the small hydrophobic IOMNPs are generated from the nucleation of monomers, and larger particles can be subsequently obtained through the seeded growth process (Jun, Choi, & Cheon, 2006). Moreover, the average diameter of IOMNPs can also be tuned by altering the ratios between organometallic precursors, solvents, stabilizing surfactants, and other reaction parameters, such as the heating rate and reaction time. However, thermal decomposition is confronted with some potential challenges, such as the additional surface modifications of particles, which are often required to afford hydrophilicity, and a strict product purification process, which is also essential prior to the in vivo application, because toxic solvents are sometimes used.
